Graphs of derivatives

From the graph of a function, we can find the graph of its derivative by thinking about when the original graph is increasing, decreasing or stationary, and what this means for the sign of the derivative.

Function Derivative Graph of derivative
Stationary \(f'(x)=0\) Has a root here
Increasing \(f'(x)>0\) Lies above the \(x\)-axis
Decreasing \(f'(x)<0\) Lies below the \(x\)-axis

Example

The graph \(y=f(x)\) has two stationary points, so the graph of the derivative will have two roots (at the \(x\)-coordinates of the stationary points). Thinking about the sign of \(f'(x)\) on the three intervals helps us to construct the graph of the derivative shown below.
